Taylor, like a lot of other Republicans back then, wanted the government to interpret the Constitution really strictly. He wanted a super small government with only the powers that the Constitution says it has. He knew that a big government is expensive and might turn into a dictatorship, but he also thought that just following the letter of the law without thinking about the people who wrote it could be bad too. He even thought the Declaration of Independence was like a blueprint for the US, because it says we're a bunch of independent states, not just one country.

Going back to the graph, it's pretty clear that the number of commuter log submissions dropped dramatically in the third month of the project. It was pretty discouraging, and I'm still trying to figure out why that happened. Winter had just hit the New England campus, which probably explains some of the decline in people biking or walking to school. At the same time, it was the end of the fall semester, and people were super busy finishing up their schoolwork and dealing with grades. Filling out the commuter log just slipped their minds, I guess. Plus, December is the start of the holiday season, and everyone was either busy or on winter break, so it's no wonder that the log submissions were way down. Classes didn't resume until late January, which maybe explains the low numbers for that month too. But the low numbers in February still don't make sense. We were worried that people's initial enthusiasm for the project would wear off over time, and that's exactly what happened. We tried to combat this with Carpool Challenge Week in March, which did end up boosting log submissions for that month. So, we faced a couple of major challenges: keeping people engaged when they naturally lose interest, and dealing with the holiday and semester breaks that come with higher ed. 

Another big problem is that people love driving their cars because it's so convenient and independent, which is just part of our culture. To get people to switch to alternative modes of commuting, we need to offer some serious incentives. We gave out gift cards to local places, but it would have been cool to see how bigger prizes, like a free bike or hybrid car, would have affected participation. That might have helped us avoid that dip in engagement. The prizes we offered didn't change over time, and while the gift cards were nice at first, announcing bigger prizes in December and January might have made a huge difference. We might have seen way higher participation rates instead of declining ones.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is a super flexible security that's like a stock, but tracks an index, commodity, or a bunch of assets like an index fund.  You get the benefits of owning a single stock, like selling short and buying on margin, and the diversification of an index fund, but with lower expense ratios than the average mutual fund.  The downside is that you'll have to pay a commission on trades, just like with stocks.  On the plus side, there are tons of ETFs to choose from.  But, it's always smart to double-check the benefits, like diversification, to make sure they're really there and how much they're worth.  For this project, we're taking a closer look at the ETF IHF and comparing it to its top 10 holdings to see if owning a single ETF is as good as owning a diversified portfolio of those 10 stocks.  We also want to know if there's a better way to mix and match those stocks for a better return and lower risk.

To make things simpler, we're only looking at the top 10 holdings that make up 63.58% of the ETF's assets.  These are the stocks that are included below.  To figure out how well these 10 stocks represent the entire ETF, we're calculating their Beta and Return as if they were the only stocks in the portfolio.  We're using the current percentages of the holdings to do this.  The chart below shows the results.

From the chart, it's clear that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings would have a return that's 6.11% higher than the ETF, which is a 16% increase.  It also shows that the Beta of the top 10 holdings is .12 lower than the ETF's Beta.  So far, it looks like a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could be a better bet, but we need to make sure the difference is real and not just a fluke.  To do this, we're looking at the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and comparing it to the ETF's standard deviation.

One of Edgar Allan Poe's favorite poems is Dream-Land. In Dream-Land, Poe uses the term "Thulé", which he likely got from Virgil. But there's a catch - Virgil might not have been the first person to use this term. It's also possible that Poe borrowed it from another source, especially since he was super into German authors. 

This is significant because it shows just how familiar Poe was with Goethe's writing. Some people, like Karl J. Arndt, think that Poe was even copying Goethe's style. Arndt wrote about this in his book Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon. 

You can find a whole poem called "The King of Thulé" in the second part of Goethe's famous poetic drama Faust. It's about a king who's really upset after his wife dies and gives him a special goblet. He starts drinking a lot and crying, and eventually decides it's time to die. He gives away all his stuff except the goblet and then jumps off a cliff. Sounds pretty similar to the King of Thule in Dream-Land, right? Maybe it's like a darker version of Poe's own struggles with loss and addiction.

Faust was also made into a romantic drama by H P Grattan in 1842, just before Poe used the term Thulé in The Pit and the Pendulum. Poe actually mentions Thulé twice in his writing - once in The Pit and the Pendulum and twice in Dream-Land. You could say that "The King of Thule" and Dream-Land are like two poems that go together. In Dream-Land, the speaker talks about how dark and lonely Thulé is, and how he's haunted by dead friends. It's like he's stepping into Goethe's poem.

Goethe was a huge deal, and Poe must have known about him because of his respect for Tennyson. Poe said that he admired Tennyson, and Tennyson was really into Goethe. Poe would have seen Goethe's work in all the reproductions that were happening after the original publication. So, it's no surprise that Poe was influenced by Goethe's style.

I've been wondering if a customer who slipped and fell on an applesauce spill in a grocery store could get punitive damages under California law if the store manager was really careless. He was told about the spill twice, but he didn't clean it up for 30 minutes because he was eating dinner. A judge might not dismiss the customer's claim right away. To get punitive damages, the customer will have to show that the manager was super reckless and knew how bad his actions would be. The customer can argue that the manager should have known this because a bunch of other customers had slipped and fallen at the store before, and he still didn't do anything about it. Even though this isn't the strongest reason, it's a pretty good one, considering that six people had slipped and fallen in the store that year, and the manager still didn't take care of the problem.

It turns out that the manager, Paul Martin, was really relaxed about cleaning up the spill. On October 13th, one of his employees, Rich Wayne, told him about it, but Martin said he was on a break and didn't have time for customer complaints. Another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, reminded him an hour later, and he gave the same response. An hour after that, the customer, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell on the spill and got really hurt. Before that, five other people had slipped and fallen in the store that year. Now Palmer is suing the store for money to cover her medical bills and some extra money to teach the store a lesson. We're thinking about whether to ask the judge to throw out that part of the lawsuit.

In California, a customer can get punitive damages if the store did something really bad on purpose or was super reckless and didn't care about the consequences. The law says that if the store didn't mean to hurt the customer, but still did something really bad, it's like they did it on purpose. This can happen if the store knew what they were doing would hurt someone, but they went ahead and did it anyway. A court said that's what happened in a case called Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., where the store was aware of the risks and still didn't do anything to prevent them.

It's been almost four years since I took a course on Islam at CBC, which got me thinking about how people view the religion.  One thing that really stuck out was the debate over whether Islam is actually a hostile faith - a question that's even more relevant now than back then.  Looking back on what's happened since 9/11, I've seen the media's attitude swing from being super negative to being super tolerant of Islam in the US.  I mean, can you imagine a presidential candidate with a Muslim background like Barack Obama in 2001?  It's crazy.

What really got me was reading the Prophet's biography.  From what I knew, I thought Muhammad was all about forcing people to convert to Islam, but the biography paints a totally different picture - he's more like a martyr who's humble and misunderstood.  People come to him because they're convinced by his teachings, not because he's forcing them to join.  It's weird, because there are some pretty cool similarities between Jesus and Muhammad's alleged miracles, like the time Muhammad fed a group of people with some mutton and milk.  But it's always bugging me that the writers of the biography seem to be trying to make Muhammad out to be this humble guy who doesn't need to prove anything.  It's like they're trying to take credit for Jesus' life and message by linking it to Muhammad.  
 
I also have some issues with the way the stories in the biography are presented.  A lot of them are second-hand or third-hand accounts, which just makes me think they're not entirely trustworthy.  It's like they're trying to prove that people converted to Islam of their own free will, but it comes across as kinda suspicious.  What really gets my goat is that they're trying to make Muhammad out to be this perfect, godly guy who's humble and wise.  But the historical record says otherwise - and I wonder if Muslims today know the real story behind Muhammad's rise to power.

It appears that Jesus' teachings and the beliefs he held during his lifetime got lost in the shuffle as Christianity continued to evolve after he was gone.  If you look at the history of Christianity in general terms, you can see a pattern where the original teachings have gradually drifted away.  Nowadays, it's more and more clear that people are becoming more open-minded and there's a growing trend of progress.  While traditionalists will resist any change from what they were taught, their numbers might not be enough to sway the masses.  Within Christianity, a deeper understanding of history will grow over the coming years, and people will start to differentiate between the ideas that were added to the religion over time and what Jesus originally intended.  It might take a long time, decades or even centuries, but the outcome is inevitable:  There will be a major shift in the way Christianity has been progressing.  The trend will reverse itself, moving backward until all that's left is the original stuff that Jesus brought to the world on behalf of God, before other thinkers started making their own claims.  When this shift starts spreading through the US and Europe, a lot of people will begin to worship in the same way they did back in Jesus' time, following his ideas alone.  The church as an institution will still be a major force, but because the theological clock will be turned back, the huge variety in Christianity will start to shrink into more and more uniformity of beliefs and practices.  Instead of seeing lots of differences between regions, denominations, and divisions, people will start to notice more and more similarities.  History is full of great reversals like this - think about how Christians used to be persecuted and killed by the Roman Empire, but then the empire became a Christian institution, or how our country went from African-American slavery to African-American leadership.  A similar big reversal is coming in the Christian world, undoing history to get back to the source, and in the process, undoing the diversity that's developed over time.  A crucial part of this process will be understanding Jesus' words as metaphors, rather than taking them as literal statements.  So, what happened since Jesus' time?

Looking way back into history, we can see that the only thing that existed was Judaism, which is the foundation for the Christian religion.  By the time the Romans took over Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., monotheism, the idea of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were already at the core of Judaism.  But even back then, the Jewish population wasn't a single, unified group - they split into different factions, like the Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the majority of regular people.

I think that The Jungle really brings out how selfish and self-centered people are deep down. They only care about themselves and making their own lives awesome, but they never think about anyone below them. This is shown in many ways in The Jungle. The owners and managers of the big factories are a total example of this. All they care about is making their companies huge and powerful. They don't even think about anyone or anything that gets in their way or gets harmed because of their stuff. Upton Sinclair is really good at painting a picture of just how bad the pollution from these factories is in his book. He says, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world". He's trying to show just how much damage all this pollution is causing. The owners don't care if anyone gets hurt. They don't care about all the smoke coming out of the factories or the gross stuff from the thousands of pens around Packingtown.

The owners and managers also didn't care about their employees at all. They would do anything to make or save a little more money. "So from the top to bottom the place is just a huge mix of jealousies and hatreds; there's no loyalty or decency anywhere, there's no place where a person counts for anything against a dollar". They made their employees work super long hours and then would just get rid of loads of people without any notice or help finding a new job. During the time The Jungle is set in, there were hardly any laws to protect workers' safety or well-being. This let the managers and owners do whatever they wanted, making their employees speed up and work in terrible conditions. The people who lived and worked in Packingtown were basically expected to deal with the awful conditions, both on the job and at home. There were no organizations or agencies to help the workers. There were unions, but they often made more money off the poor workers than they helped them. The workers were treated so badly and had no way to escape the system of Packingtown that they were basically treated like slaves. "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

A lot of authors use different techniques in their writing to get a specific emotion or attitude across to their readers. Some of these techniques work way better than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald, the author of The Great Gatsby, uses a lot of these techniques in his novel. Sometimes, he pairs words together in a way that doesn't usually go together to create a certain vibe about a subject. Other times, he gives a certain meaning to a symbol and then uses it for the same purpose. 

One technique Fitzgerald uses often is building up a meaning for colors and then later using that meaning to remind readers of a particular feeling around an important thing. He does this with colors like gold, green, white, gray, red, and pink. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald starts giving meaning to white and gray and then later uses that meaning to create a certain feeling about something.

The meaning Fitzgerald gives to white and gray is all about uniformity and sameness. He shows this by using these colors a lot at the beginning of the novel. For example, everyone is always wearing white. Daisy and Jordan are always "in white", and even the settings are described with white and gray: Nick wears "white flannels" to Gatsby's party, Tom wears a "white shirt" when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is "powdered milky white". The only time people aren't wearing white is when Nick gives his impression of Gatsby's party. Fitzgerald even defines these colors by using them to describe everyday, unimportant things like buildings, people, and names. 

After Fitzgerald has built up the meaning of white and gray, he starts using them to show how unimportant or boring something is. He does this by using these colors to describe Daisy, who used to be a bigger character, but now feels more like just a boring addition to the story. Fitzgerald does this by describing Daisy wearing white or gray, like when she's dressed in white in a little white roadster. The readers start to see her as just a part of the uniform, something that Gatsby wants and longs for. He does this again and again to make this point about Daisy being a boring addition. For example, there's a "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" and she's wearing white again before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

San Diego County is super fertile due to its pleasant, sunny climate. They grow all sorts of yummy stuff like tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squashes, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There's a huge demand for organic food in the area, with lots of people waiting months to get their hands on it. People also love buying organic eggs and milk. Many of these farms even let you come and explore their operations, hike, or go birdwatching - it's like getting a free mini-vacation. This type of farm can help the landowner get government cash while keeping the land nice and healthy, which is awesome because it lets people visit and learn stuff.

Not only does this type of farming make a bunch of money, but it also brings in all sorts of cool wildlife because they don't use yucky chemicals. However, it's way more work and can be more expensive than regular farming because you have to get rid of pests and weeds the hard way and manually fertilize the soil. You also might lose more crops, and a small farm can't compete with those giant, industrial farms when it comes to efficiency. They also have to do extra stuff like planting special crops to keep the soil healthy and removing invasive species, which costs more time and money.

This land I chose for this example is in an awesome spot near the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It's 160 acres of chaparral, non-native grassland, and oak woodland right next to the Cleveland National Forest. The East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan is all over the area, and they're still reviewing it. It's home to over a hundred species of plants and animals, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, and the California gnatcatcher, which are all in danger of disappearing. This land has been home to Native Americans for a super long time and was later used for cattle ranching and selling cordwood in the late 1800s. It was part of an original homestead patent, so it probably used to be used for grazing and wood production for a while.

I picked a piece of land from a real estate site and looked into government programs to see what a small farmer might be able to do to make farming more affordable and still save the wildlife. I chose an organic farm in the same area as a model of what someone might try to do with this land.

Culture's impact on a negotiation is significant. Culture isn't just what it is, but also what it isn't and what it signifies. It's not a single, unified thing, nor is it the same across the board. General statements like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" are way too broad and pretty simplistic. It's more productive for a negotiator to understand the importance of a culture to the specific negotiation at hand and how that culture's attitude will affect the discussion. When you encounter a foreign culture, you experience it in a way that relates to your own, which leads to comparisons.

Getting to know a foreign culture or mindset can involve studying its history, understanding its biases, or learning about its traditions. Rather than judging or trying to change it, you need to accept it for what it is and work within its boundaries, especially when negotiating. If you're in a weaker position, showing respect for the other culture and its traditions can really help you break down any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It's worth noting that culture isn't just about national or international differences. Companies often have their own unique corporate culture, which can vary greatly from one company to another. For instance, some companies might expect employees to work long hours, while others have a more relaxed schedule. Look at how different companies in the same country can have distinct corporate cultures, from dress codes to communication styles to hiring practices. Some companies might even have different corporate cultures within the same company, depending on the region or location.

Understanding a culture's values is also key, because it helps you understand the "why" behind it. If saving face or maintaining harmony are important in a culture, you can bet that a negotiator won't publicly embarrass their company or superior to get ahead in a negotiation. On the other hand, a negotiator from a culture that values a tough bargain won't necessarily settle for a quick agreement. Knowing these generalities beforehand is crucial before sitting down at the negotiating table. However, it's also really helpful to learn something about your opponent on a personal level to make the negotiation go smoothly.

There's this famous phrase from Psalm 14 in the Christian Bible: "The fool hath said in his heart, 'There is no God.'" It's actually the starting point for St. Anselm's argument about God's existence. We're also gonna look at Thomas Aquinas, and since their ideas pretty much support the same concept, we'll assume they're both right about God being the one from the Bible. If their God wasn't from the Bible, it'd be hard to compare their arguments since they're really trying to prove one specific version of God exists. So, we're gonna start by thinking they both believe in the same God.

To get a feel for their ideas, let's look at St. Anselm's first. Anselm says that we can figure out God by looking inside ourselves. He thinks that since we can't really imagine a world without God, it's proof that God exists in our minds. This idea can get a bit confusing, but basically, Anselm's saying that we can know God just by thinking about what we already know to be true. That's kinda like having faith – it's not about needing proof, it's about trusting what's inside your head. This is a big deal in Christianity because it's about trusting in something that might not be proven.

St. Thomas Aquinas took a different approach. He thinks we can prove God exists using logic and facts, no faith needed. This would actually be pretty cool for spreading the word of Christianity because people wouldn't need to believe something just because they're told to – they could believe it because it makes sense. Aquinas came up with five separate arguments to show that God must exist because of the way the world works: change, cause and effect, things that are temporary, levels of perfection, and things working together in harmony. Each one basically says that since we can see how all these things need a creator, we can know God must be that creator without even seeing God.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would eventually be known as Buddha was born. Throughout his life, this prince made the choice to leave behind worldly life and achieve enlightenment, which led to the establishment of Buddhism. Over time, the teachings have led to the formation of the most traditional form of Buddhism, which is often referred to as Theravada. As the religion has aged – it's now around 2500 years old – it's undergone a lot of changes. This is clear when looking at countries like Sri Lanka, where the Theravada community has developed unique traditions and celebrations, like the water-cutting ceremony. This ceremony is observed by both monks and lay followers, but interestingly, it wasn't something that Buddha himself ever taught about. The differences between past and present can be seen in both the surface-level customs and the core teachings of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community has had to adapt its guiding principles over the years, both when influenced by external forces, like those from outside the Buddhist community, and internal ones, like changes within the community itself.

To make sense of this discussion, it's essential to understand some key concepts that will be used throughout. 'Internal' refers to forces generated by members of the Buddhist community, regardless of whether they're monks or lay followers. 'External' forces come from outside the Buddhist community. A 'hostile' force is one that aims to harm or damage the community, often due to a negative perception of Buddhism. A 'benign' force, on the other hand, doesn't intend to harm or help the community, but may end up doing so as a byproduct.

First and foremost, we need to explore the fundamentals of Theravada Buddhism – the core teachings that it's built upon. Buddhists find refuge in the 'triple gem': the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially made up of the three baskets (Tripitaka) of Buddhist scripture. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas (Buddhist teachings), the Vinaya Pitaka contains the rules for living, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka includes the more abstract, metaphysical concepts of Buddhism, such as the idea that there is no permanent soul (Anatta), that life is marked by inherent suffering (Dukkha), and that everything is impermanent (Anicca). Recognizing these concepts is crucial in breaking free from Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth. This cycle, along with lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion), will cease when one achieves enlightenment. In the Vinaya Pitaka, guidelines for living are outlined. For lay followers, there are five basic principles to follow (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not engage in immoral behavior, and I shall not consume intoxicating substances). Monks, on the other hand, must adhere to many more rules. The core of Buddhism, however, is the four noble truths: first, that life is suffering (Dukkha); second, that attachment causes suffering; and third, that suffering can be overcome.

The US and Mexico were at odds for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893, due to a longstanding rivalry. This tension was at its peak during the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, when the US defeated Mexico and took control of Texas and the American Southwest (Diehl and Goerts, 2000, p. 145). Many other conflicts occurred between the two nations, but they eventually cooled off just before World War I. The initial conflict started with disagreements over issues like religion, culture, and tradition, as well as a clash of material interests (Schmitt, 1974, p. 30-31). 

This situation isn't unique - many neighboring nations have similar rivalries. When countries share a border, their conflicting interests can lead to the formation of opposing stances between them. The US and Mexico aren't the only example of this; other nations with a history of border disputes often have similar issues. David M. Pletcher notes that Mexico and Cuba are the only Latin American nations that have had long-standing diplomatic troubles with the US (1977, p. 41).

One major point of contention between the US and Mexico was their religious differences, a problem that has plagued many nations throughout history. Sally Frahm points out that Americans were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy in the 18th and 19th centuries, just as they were opposed to fascism and communism in the 20th century (2001, p. 86). Like the ideological struggle between the US and the Soviet Union, this rivalry was based on differing values and interests, but in this case, they stemmed from the US and Mexico's contrasting religious preferences. This distrust was inherited from their colonial rulers, the English and Spanish, making it difficult for the two nations to establish friendly relations.

According to Diehl and Goerts (2000), there were 17 disputes between Mexico and the US during this 57-year period, mostly related to territorial issues, such as border raids and frontier problems. Border bandits and outlaws from American towns were a significant problem until the US and Mexico took military action to secure their borders (Schmitt, 1974, p. 97). Schmitt notes that the rivalry began to subside as Mexico became increasingly dependent on the US and eventually ended as the US shifted its focus from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico (1974, p. 109-110).

It's been 15 years since I was taken down by a sickness that caught me completely off guard. Back then I was working as a nurse because, as a kid, I didn't have the stability and security I craved. People kept saying things like 'You'll always find work - people will always get sick' so I picked nursing over my true passions, which were science and journalism. Even though I had dreams of being both, it was easier to rely on a steady income. 

I'm now 46 and single, broke, and unable to work because of this illness. I've been living off Social Security Disability for 15 years, and to this day, I have nothing that's truly mine. Each day feels like a struggle, an assault on my sense of security, safety, and confidence. Nothing feels secure anymore, but one thing I know for sure - if it weren't for my family and a few close friends, I wouldn't have made it this far. Even when disaster strikes, you don't feel as strong as you thought you'd be.

My point is that life is full of unexpected emergencies, big and small. No matter how prepared you are, some things are just too overwhelming to handle on your own. The U.S. needs to stop putting all its eggs in the government basket, which is crumbling anyway. Instead, I'd rather see Americans learn to trust and help each other again, to ask for help without hesitation.

The U.S. Conservatives keep talking about rugged individualism, but the truth is, our ancestors' success in tough times wasn't about going it alone - it was about compassion, mutual respect, and sharing resources. The pioneers who trekked across the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by themselves.

So, by all means, be prepared. I have a disaster kit stocked with first aid supplies, water purifiers, and emergency essentials. I've got flashlights, batteries, candles, and canned goods. If you have the means and resources for a small farm, that's a great idea too. But while you're at it, take the time to know your neighbors - it might just save you in a pinch.

So, why do organisms evolve the way they do? Are there any rules or limitations that affect the direction of evolutionary change? Even back in 1917, D’Arcy Thompson said that zoologists had barely started to think about describing simple organic shapes using math. Nowadays, it's still pretty much the same. Lately, scientists have tried using math to figure out how mollusks' skeletons grow and change over time. Our research is focused on using math to understand how animals like Prunum change and grow. We're combining math with experiments to learn more about how evolution works.

We looked at X-ray pictures of Prunum shells to find patterns that we could use to create models of how shells might change over time. We fed this data into a computer program called CerioShell (Stone, 1995) and used it to imagine how shells could be different. These ideas are being combined with other studies to help us understand how big changes happened in this group of animals.

If you think about a shell as a tube that moves through space over time, it's kind of like a big spiral staircase. The different turns of the shell are called whorls, and they're connected by a line called a suture. The biggest whorl is usually the last one, and the other whorls are called the spire. The pointy top of the spire is called the apex, and the other end is the base. The animal sticks out of its shell through a hole called the aperture.

We can look at a shell from different angles - apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural. A way to count the whorls is to look at the shell from the top and draw a line where the first suture starts. Then, we count the whorls from that line, estimating a quarter of a whorl if it's not a whole number.

A shell can be thought of as a series of holes that move through space and time as the animal builds its shell. We can track the path of these holes by looking at the center of each whorl and the size of the hole. This path can be represented mathematically and graphically. Once we have a math formula, we can change the parameters and see how it affects the way the shell grows.

The rate of neonatal and infant deaths in Indonesia hasn't really changed over the past ten years.  It's weird, because the country is doing pretty well in other areas like water and sanitation, but when it comes to keeping babies and moms safe, they're way behind where they need to be by 2015. I'm gonna get into the reasons later, but basically, it's time to make the whole health system stronger instead of just focusing on individual programs.

Indonesia has made some progress with getting medical workers at births, with 72% of births meeting this target now. But it's a little misleading because they include midwives who can't do much if something goes wrong, so a lot of moms still die from things like bleeding after delivery. Plus, it's not like they're getting better care for the little kids either - in fact, they're getting worse. We don't have all the info on post-birth care, but it's pretty clear that's another problem area.

C-sections are still way too low, only 4%, and it's even worse in rural areas where it's only 2%. That shows how uneven healthcare is around the country, with mostly rich people getting the good stuff. And to make things worse, there's a huge gap in healthcare access between the poor and the rich - it's like a 27% difference. So, the poor people are basically stuck without access to healthcare because they can't afford it.

Now we have to figure out how to fix this, and the main question is whether to focus on improving specific programs or strengthening the whole health system. It's tempting to do the specific programs because they're more focused, but they also have some major drawbacks. For one thing, it's hard to get funding for other areas when someone's getting a lot of attention for one thing. And with too many programs going on at once, you end up with a bunch of duplicate services and a huge mess of paperwork and supplies.

Victorian novels are known for their meticulous attention to detail and their focus on the high society of the time.  However, two novels that stray from this tradition are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights.  Both novels feature an element of mystery and a penchant for the bizarre, which is unusual for the period, and this adds depth to the characters; giving insight into their motives and emotions.  

And then, a jumble of confusing ideas started racing through his mind.  He was still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were arguing loudly; the words they said were still echoing in his ears; and when he suddenly snapped back to reality, he realized he was talking to them.  Then, the sound of gunfire startled him, and he was bombarded by a cacophony of screams and shouts.  Everything around him was a blur, and he felt an overwhelming sense of pain that refused to subside.

These two novels often use mystery through dreamlike states, though the content and purpose varies in each case.  In Oliver Twist, these strange events often reveal Oliver's innermost thoughts, his fears, and his awareness of the harsh reality around him.  When Oliver is shot in the end, the scene is revisited in chapter 28, and he relives it vividly, as if it were a dream, while desperately trying to find help.  The passage highlights Oliver's lack of control over the events that unfolded, as well as his dire circumstances, which are evident through his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit.  The shooting overwhelms him, numbing all his senses; he's unaware of the 'unseen force' that's taking him away.  His despair is replayed before him, now constant and linked with fear rather than shock.  With Oliver being overwhelmed, the question arises as to whose actions led to his misfortune, since it was certainly not his own.  This shooting reinforces the notion that Oliver has little control over anything, not even his own life, as he fails to even attempt to take control of an event's outcome.  A growing sense of defeat in Oliver is also implied, as if old Fagin had broken him, forcing him to accept this despair and lose his ability to react.  Otherwise, it can be assumed that Oliver would have made some effort, at least to save his own life.


The day passed all too quickly – it was gone before he knew it – and night fell again, long and oppressive in its silence, but brief in its fleeting moments.

I used to work at an after-school program where I helped elementary students with their schoolwork. My specialty was English and reading, but I tried to assist them in whatever subjects they were struggling with. I was asked to work with this kid named Adrian, who was having some serious trouble reading. At first, I thought he was just having a tough time, but it turned out that something weird was going on - he could pronounce certain letters perfectly, but others were way off. I knew he was of Latino descent, but he spoke perfect English, which was really weird. We struggled to figure out what was going on until the day I met his mom. She didn't speak a word of English, only Spanish, and I was barely learning it at the time. We managed to communicate somehow, but it hit me like a ton of bricks when I realized that Adrian knew how to read just fine - he just didn't know the English alphabet. I don't know if that insight really helped him much, but I hope he's doing okay now.

I share that story to highlight the problem of language barriers in schools, especially here in California. It's not always as obvious as we think - even if a kid speaks perfect English, reading can still be super tough. Everyone agrees that this problem exists, so what's the solution? For Adrian, it was pretty simple: one-on-one tutoring in English reading, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation. But for kids who barely speak English, it's way more complicated. There's no single answer. Some people swear by the dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes, or a combination of all of the above. The key is to try a bit of everything.

The dual language system is a great idea - not just for kids who speak Spanish at home, but for all kids. It's been shown that kids in these programs outperform their peers academically. A lot of people are scared that it's a waste of resources, but that's not true. If we made these programs the norm, not the exception, all kids would benefit from them. So, how do we make it happen? Do we need all teachers to be bilingual? No, that's unrealistic. But we can definitely have special aides, tutors, or whatever, who are bilingual. It's not that hard.

Most of us are led to believe that there's something much bigger than ourselves out there, something we can barely wrap our heads around. We're often sent to places like Sunday school or Temple to learn about it, or we search within for answers on our own. Some people just go along with the religions their parents taught them, while others totally reject the idea that there's anything more to life than what they can see and touch. We might adopt one set of values, only to later switch to another. Wherever we go, we're trying to figure out who we are and what we believe through our own special ways of looking at spirituality. We're on a quest to find the light in the dark and guide ourselves out of the shadows and into the sunlight.

My dad told me that cardinals are his favorite bird when I asked him, and we sat on our porch listening to the rain pound against the tin roof. The gutters were overflowing, drowning the plants along the porch edge. He stared out at the rain, lost in thought, his eyes half searching, half remembering. He'd lost a lot of weight over the past few months, and his clothes hung loose on his body. His hair was thinning out, too. He didn't want to talk about how sick he was, and I was too scared to bring it up. If we talked about it, it would make it feel more real. So I just hugged him, sat back down, and joined him in staring out into the rain.

My dad passed away in December, just five days after my birthday. The chemo and radiation had kept him alive for a few more months, but it was just prolonging the suffering. I couldn't help but wonder, what was the point of it all? I stopped going to church, and at night, I just lay awake, wondering if God was even listening. I knew that if God was real, he'd stopped caring about me a long time ago.

I didn't want to see my dad die, so I didn't. I couldn't watch the man who created me slip away. I wanted to remember him for who he was, not how he died. And I knew my dad would've wanted it that way too. So I curled up in a ball and waited for the news. Nobody even bothered calling me.

The term "Gothic Novel" is actually an oxymoron, combining "old" and "new" elements, as Ian Watt so astutely points out in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. This style has been met with both praise and criticism, with some dismissing it as lacking depth, while others hail its ability to evoke the "terrible sublime" (Burke). At the time of its creation, Horace Walpole's "A Gothic Story" (as he called it) blended old theatrical elements with new, modern ideas to give birth to the Gothic genre. The Gothic style borrowed heavily from medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions, which were already seen as old-fashioned and unsophisticated compared to the more modern societal and literary advancements of the time. It was this unexpected mix of the old and the new that allowed the Gothic genre to endure and remain fresh to readers even centuries later.

One of the most significant features of Gothic novels is the idea of Chivalry, which was a major part of medieval culture. In The Castle of Otranto, Walpole took this concept and adapted it to suit his story, creating a knight-like character that embodied the qualities that were seen as lacking in his own time. Walpole was writing in a tumultuous era, and his work reflects his fears about the state of society. He may have believed that the morality and goodness that were once associated with the Gothic era had been lost in the present, leading him to idealize and romanticize the past. This is evident in the character of Frederic, who is described as a prince, a sufferer, and a gallant knight. His portrayal is a classic example of the chivalric ideals that were prominent in medieval culture, and it sets the stage for the excess that would become a hallmark of the Gothic genre (Walpole 66).

The process of moving goods from the customer's order to the final product delivery is called supply chain management. This concept was first introduced by consultant Keith Oliver back in 1982. He described it as a series of processes that work together to deliver customer needs efficiently. There are six main components to a well-functioning supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Managers use these elements to provide top-notch customer service.

First up is production, the foundation of the entire supply chain process. It's where you figure out when, why, where, and how products get made. To succeed, managers need to know what customers want, and they can find that out by studying the market. Once they've got a handle on customer demand, they can decide what products to make, how many, and where to produce them. They've got to choose a production location that'll meet customer needs for both volume and quality. Next, they focus on scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment to keep things running smoothly.

Getting production right is huge – every detail matters. If you mess up, it can cost a lot of time and money in the long run. For example, my past experience working at Wal-Mart and Target taught me that having clear processes in place is key. From employee uniforms to receiving shipments, every step should be outlined to avoid confusion and miscommunication.

The second key element is supply, which involves making strategic decisions about a company's capabilities and partnerships. This might involve deciding which production divisions to use for a single product or outsourcing certain tasks to other companies. The goal is to create velocity – delivering quality and flexibility while keeping costs low.

It's this sign I saw that really caught my attention: "Hitler is alive in Burma". I was walking down the street and Ellen Page from that movie Juno was standing there holding a weird sign with Sharpie writing on it. Burma is this country in Southeast Asia where a super strict government took over in 1962 and hasn't really changed since. There was this huge protest in 2007, it was called the Saffron Revolution, because they wore these bright orange robes, and it was the first time people had protested in like a decade. But things escalated quickly and the government started getting really violent. They rounded up all the journalists and even killed a Japanese photographer just for being there. The government said like 13 people died, but this army colonel said that's way off and that there were actually thousands.

It's not like this is new or anything. For as long as we've had civilization, governments have been trying to shut down any dissent and keep everyone in line. Even ancient Roman emperors thought they were chosen by the gods and could control everything. Japanese emperors thought they were gods too, and our current president, I'm pretty sure, has weekly meetings with some dude from the Republic Party, Ted Haggard. There have been some really crazy events like that, like the Tiananmen Square protest in 1989 where students and intellectuals were killed by the government, and the Rwandan genocide in the 90s where the government killed tons of people just because of who they were. And then there's the whole Hitler thing, but that's pretty self explanatory.

Duke Ellington's impact on jazz is largely due to his long career and incredible musical abilities. His piano playing might not be super obvious in many of the songs we're looking at, but as a composer, Ellington was amazing at writing complex pieces that let individual band members shine. He'd create the foundation for a soloist to improvise freely, and also write tightly orchestrated parts that made the most of each band member's style. By doing this, Ellington helped bring out the unique tone of the entire orchestra, making each piece its own. He was a master at understanding how the different band members sounded individually and how they worked together, which is why he wrote some of the most groundbreaking pieces in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary talks about Ellington's innovative sound and techniques, using Creole Love Call as an example of how he used voice like a jazz instrument throughout his career. This was basically an early experiment with using vocal textures and colors without worrying about lyrics. It also shows Ellington's skill at complementing the style of his soloists, which is something he did really well his whole career. This slow, bluesy twelve-bar piece is a great example - it's got six different sections, each one showcasing the band's different sounds:

The first chorus is a call-and-response thing with voice and reeds, where the voice starts off smooth and gets rougher towards the end. The second chorus has a muted trumpet solo that adds some extra flavor to the basic melody. The third chorus is a sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a simple piano phrase. The fourth chorus is like a big echo of the first one, with the brass and reed sections trading calls and responses. The fifth chorus is the climax, with the reeds taking over the call-and-response and the brass and rhythm sections adding some syncopated rhythms. And the sixth chorus is like the first one, but this time the voice gets all growly and does some instrumental-style soloing.

Ellington's use of voice to add tone color to his music is just one example of the cool stuff he did. In Hot and Bothered, he combined his tight orchestration skills with his ear for tone, using a call-and-response phrase between Bubber Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing to create a rich sound. And in It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing), he made great use of Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton's muted trombone to introduce the melody.

There was this huge emptiness inside her that she just couldn't shake off. It was a feeling she's had ever since she was 14 and still lingered on at 17. It started as a craving for something, but she had no idea what. She figured out that it wasn't just about things, but about people, specifically - but no one had ever caught her eye. Some guys had tried to get her attention, but every attempt just felt forced. She often found herself wondering what could be the reason behind this crazy desire. Over the years, she'd come up with some theories, but none of them really made sense to her. So, she just kept on living, always questioning her feelings.

At home, everything was usually chill. She had pretty cool parents who hardly ever argued. When they did, it was usually about her wanting to be her own person. That's because she was super outgoing and fun, like the complete opposite of her calm parents. Today, though, was a different story. As she was looking for some inspiration, she heard a blood-curdling scream from the kitchen and her mom's voice. She rushed in to find her mom on the ground, looking like she was in a lot of pain. "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" she frantically asked as she ran to her side and put a hand on her to help. Her mom said "Ow... swee - ty, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital" in a really short breath. She could tell her mom was in a lot of pain, so she helped her get off the ground and into the car.

The hospital had that weird smell of disinfectant and illness, but she was too worried about her mom to feel scared. She quickly grabbed a wheelchair and rushed in to get help. A bunch of worried faces showed up, but her mind was just on her mom. They got her mom onto a bed and took her to see a doctor. Her daughter was left to sit and stress.

Apparently, her mom fell off a step stool while trying to get a vase from a super high cabinet. That's how she ended up in the hospital.

This study aimed to figure out if sticking to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), which can be measured by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score", would help lower the risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke. The aMed diet is an adjusted version of the Med diet that's loaded with more plant foods like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes, and less saturated fat and animal products. It also allows for some booze.

We already knew from prior studies that eating the Med diet was linked to lower heart disease risk and death, but those studies didn't focus on stroke alone. This study looked at 74,886 women aged 38 to 63, who were part of a huge study of female nurses in the US. The researchers tracked their eating habits over 20 years using special questionnaires. About 95% of the women stuck with the study the whole time, and the questionnaires were double-checked to make sure they were accurate.

The researchers found out what happened to the women over the years by looking at their medical records, death certificates, and hospital info. They even made some educated guesses when they couldn't find the records. They also looked at other factors that could affect the results, like weight, smoking, exercise, and whether the women took aspirin or vitamins.

To get a better idea of the women's eating habits over time, the researchers added up their aMed scores from six different questionnaires. Then they adjusted for things that could mess up the results, like age, smoking, and weight. They used a special method called Cox proportional-hazard modeling to see how the aMed diet score affected the women's risk of heart disease and stroke.

The study showed that women who ate the Mediterranean diet had a lower risk of heart disease and stroke. Over 20 years, there were 2391 cases of heart disease, 1763 cases of stroke, and 1077 heart disease deaths. Women with the highest aMed scores were 29% less likely to get heart disease or stroke compared to those with the lowest scores.

It's been over a decade since the US hit rock bottom in 2007, and the aftermath of the financial crisis is still causing waves. Unemployment skyrocketed, the housing market tanked, and some of America's biggest corporations were left to pick up the pieces. So the question on everyone's mind is: how did this mess happen in the first place? In a nutshell, it all came down to some pretty shady and clueless decision-making by politicians who basically strong-armed banks into giving out sub-prime loans to people who couldn't afford them. At the same time, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac were being pushed to buy up these dodgy mortgages and package them into some crazy financial instruments that nobody really understood. When people started defaulting on their loans, the banks were left high and dry and had no choice but to pass the buck to all the other financial institutions they'd sold these toxic assets to.

It all started brewing back in the Clinton era, when the President was trying to get re-elected. He wanted to boost his popularity, so he relaxed some of the lending rules, which ended up setting the stage for the sub-prime disaster to come. Steve Holmes from the New York Times was onto it back in 1999, warning that Fannie Mae was taking on too much risk by pushing mortgage loans to low-income folks and that it might all come crashing down in an economic downturn. And boy, was he right.

The economy was like a house of cards, with all these fancy new mortgage types - adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations - that just made things worse. It was like a game of financial Jenga, where everyone was over-leveraging themselves in the housing market, and when the bubble burst, it was game over. The top five investment banks were stuck with a whopping $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt, which was basically a third of the US GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch got sold off cheap, Lehman Brothers went under, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley had to sell out to become commercial banks with tighter regulations. Fannie and Freddie were in even worse shape, with $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and the government had to step in to take control in 2008.

But then there's that infamous part of your story, the expositional stretch where you're supposed to flex your writing muscles, but end up putting everyone to sleep instead.  You know, the spot where your readers are either nodding off or frantically hitting the "Back" button, cursing your name in the process.  Dr. Merlin sometimes finds herself yelling at her monitor when she gets stuck in this rut, and it's not even the good kind of yelling.

Exposition isn't exactly your BFF.

Of course, you probably already know the "Show, don't tell" mantra, but Dr. Merlin still manages to get herself stuck in long, meandering passages where nothing much happens – or worse, too much happens.  It's like that pesky devil on your shoulder, urging you to get all the backstory out of the way so you can get to the good stuff (not to be confused with the other devil telling you to spill every single juicy detail about each character's childhood).

Exposition is essentially just telling the audience what's going on in simple, straightforward language.  It's like the movie version, where one character lays it all out for another in a long, rambling monologue (think "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner").  In fiction, you're the one doing the telling.

Let's take an example.  You're reading a story and you're hit with a barrage of info about the heroine: she met her beloved at such-and-such a place, they got hitched in a fancy wedding, and her hubby got whacked right in front of her.  You wouldn't expect that whole sequence to take up two whole pages, with the couple only getting a couple of lines of dialogue each.  You'd want the author to flesh out the husband's character, showing how much he loved the heroine through his words and actions.  You'd also want to see how much her life changed and improved with him around – especially if the story later reveals that's exactly what happened.  A proper introduction to the husband's character would make you care about his fate and understand the heroine's feelings, making you more invested in her story as a whole.

In short, you'd want some substance to go along with the bare-bones storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, it's your job to provide that extra oomph.  It can be tempting to rush through certain parts, but resist the urge.  Maybe you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, works the graveyard shift at a gas station, has been married twice, doesn't have kids, and dreams of owning the gas station one day – all while secretly craving Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched the news from Columbus, Ohio, on August 13, 2011. The first thing that caught my attention was a live report from NBC 4 in the morning. They had a story about a guy in Ashley, Ohio, named Shad Hostettler who stabbed his wife (they didn't mention her name, but that's not the point). The dude looked pretty sinister in his mug shot - I could tell it was evil written all over his face. They only spent about two minutes on this story since it was still developing, which I thought was just right. They mentioned that he'd stabbed her multiple times and was under arrest, but that was about it.

The next story was about a shooting that happened in the Sharon Woods area - some 18-year-old named Travis Buyers got shot and was in pretty bad shape. There were no suspects or arrests yet, and the SWAT Team was investigating. This story was real short, and I'm guessing it was because the victim was a minority and the neighborhood was a minority one too. I've noticed before that the media doesn't give the same attention to crimes involving minorities as they do to crimes involving white people. For example, if a white kid goes missing, the media is all over it, but if a minority person is a victim, it's like it barely makes the news.

They also had a story about a gunshot hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. They had some details about where it might have happened and what kind of bullet was used - a .22 caliber from a rifle, I think. Crime-Stoppers were offering a $5,000 reward for any tips that could lead to the shooter's arrest.

Next up was a story about the weather forecast for the weekend, which sounded pretty typical for Columbus - rain and thunderstorms on Saturday afternoon, with highs in the mid to low eighties. They made it clear that this was just a teaser to keep us watching, so we'd stick around.

They also had a report on a robbery at a UDF on Clime Road. They said the perpetrator was a dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie, about six feet tall and 150 pounds. What struck me was how much they emphasized his race and how dark he was - it seemed a bit excessive, if you ask me.

The last story I remember was about Rene Rodriguez, a guy who'd been convicted of being a big-time marijuana dealer from Texas. He'd been sentenced to 300 months in prison for conspiring to distribute weed to Ohio from Texas. I'm not sure what they were trying to achieve by saying "300 months" instead of "25 years" - maybe they thought it sounded harsher or something. They also mentioned he was Hispanic, but I'm not sure why that was relevant to the story.

There's something unbreakable between brothers – a connection that can't be broken or undone. This bond is made up of tons of emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty – to name just a few. Brothers know each other in a way that nobody else does, and when they look at their brother, they see a reflection of themselves. In tough times, this bond really shows its true colors, whether it's good or bad. But with these emotions comes a price. Part of understanding this bond is dealing with the consequences that come with it. When you can stare a brother in the face and see your own reflection staring back, you see yourself as you really are, not as others see you. It's in their actions and the results of those actions that you find out who they really are. In the classic novel "The Scarlet Ibis", two brothers explore this idea, and all the crazy emotions that come with it. The two boys go on a wild adventure through a super vivid landscape, but it all ends in disaster. A huge mix of bitter disappointment and intense pride comes to a head, and only one brother makes it out alive. The author conveys this theme through the characters' actions, especially the main guy, Doodle, and their interactions with each other. The narrator also plays a key role by showing us how the protagonist feels about the world and how that affects his decisions.

For the protagonist, it all comes down to one main emotion: pride. From the very beginning, when he and his little brother Doodle first go on an adventure, to their final, disastrous trip, he's always feeling resentful towards Doodle. He wanted a brother who could keep up with him and learn all the cool stuff he knew, like holding his breath and climbing trees. He wanted someone to share his fun with, like racing to the top of a big pine tree and perching in the branches. But Doodle was born with a weak heart, so it was pretty unlikely he'd ever be able to do any of those things. The protagonist's dreams were crushed when that reality hit him. He even had thoughts of getting rid of Doodle, which is pretty messed up. But when Doodle smiles at him, all his anger melts away and he feels a surge of love. This shows that his anger wasn't as strong as he thought. Deep down, he's got a soft spot for his little bro.

The brain is a super cool, super complicated machine that processes info all the time. As technology got way more advanced, people started using more and more fancy metaphors to describe the brain too. First, they compared it to a wax tablet, then a piece of papyrus, then a book, and now it's like a computer. But, it's super important to keep in mind that these metaphors aren't perfect and can lead to some pretty wacky conclusions.

So, here's how the brain works: it gets all this sensory info from our eyes, ears, and other stuff, and turns it into electrical signals. Then, the brain starts messing with this info over and over in different ways. There are two main kinds of processing: bottom-up and top-down. For example, when you look at a picture of a black box on a white background, your brain puts together tiny pieces of info like color and shape to figure out that it's a box. But then, your brain also uses what it already knows to help you figure out what you're looking at even faster.

But, there's another step - the brain decides how important the info is and whether you should be paying attention to it or not. Like, you're walking down the street and you see a bunch of blades of grass, but your brain doesn't make you notice them because they're not super important. But, if someone calls out your name in a crowded room, your brain is all like, "Hey, I should pay attention to that!"

Now, for the brain to work, it needs to store info somehow. There are different types of memory, like short-term and long-term, and sensory memory. When we first get info, we need to encode it, which is like translating it into a language the brain can understand. For example, if you see a word, your brain can figure out what it looks like, what it sounds like, or what it means. Then, the brain has to keep that info stored somehow. Scientists think that short-term memory works because it's like a special electrical signal that loops through a bunch of neurons for a little while. Long-term memory, on the other hand, might be stored in the structure of special proteins in the brain.

There are a bunch of different theories about how the brain stores knowledge, some based on how people remember things, some based on computer science, and some based on brain stuff. One theory is that the brain is like a big network with nodes that represent ideas and concepts, and the nodes are all connected because they're related. For example, if you think of the word "chair," your brain might also think of "table," which might remind you of "wooden," and so on.

Aldous Huxley warns us about the dangers of technology and the effects of the capitalistic system in his dystopian novel Brave New World. In this world, people value community over individuality and are conditioned to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are essentially pawns in a game controlled by the World Controller, who dictates their ideology. By looking at the book through the lens of Marxist theory, we can see that Huxley is questioning the growth of these systems. Marxist ideas like homogeny and reification are sprinkled throughout the novel, showing that Huxley is saying that these systems have some major flaws.

Capitalism is also criticized in the novel through the concept of false consciousness. This is where people are kept in the dark about the real relationship between different classes in society, and they're more worried about their own gain. It's like the World Controller has a tight grip on the common folks, making them want to buy, spend, and indulge in stuff. The lower classes, like the Deltas and Gammas, are basically robots, doing what they're told without any free will of their own. They're conditioned with hypnopædia to be obsessed with consuming and spending. The World Controller is behind all of this, making the lower classes think they're part of the system, when really they're just pawns.

The idea of hegemony is also used in the novel, where a small group of people are in control of the whole society. The lower classes are completely clueless about this, they're just 'buying into' an ideology that helps keep the system going. The upper classes, like the Alphas and Betas, know what's going on, but they just go along with it. But not everyone is like that, some characters like Bernard see through the system, but they're the exception.

In Brave New World, relationships between people are basically non-existent. The characters are pretty shallow, even the main ones, and they don't really have any depth. Huxley might be saying that technology and capitalism are taking away people's free will and individuality. Love and strong emotions are non-existent, and people just go through the motions. It's all pretty superficial, with guys commenting on girls' looks and girls talking about their sex lives. The fact that everyone's okay with their place in society shows how capitalism is affecting people's lives. They're all just following the rules and doing what they're told, like the proletariat in Marxist theory, who are told they're better than everyone else as long as they keep consuming and obeying.

I've been a student at University Park for like two and a half years now, which is basically four and a half semesters of trying to navigate this campus. For many of us, getting around here can be a major pain. My freshman year, I was stuck in East Halls dorm, which is basically as far east as you can go without hitting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Going to classes in places like the Willard building, which is literally in the middle of campus, could take up to 25 minutes on foot, especially when it's all gross outside. I talked to an alum who's not much older than me, and they told me that not too long ago, East Halls was basically its own separate entity from the rest of the school. There used to be this huge empty space between it and the rest of campus, but now it's all been filled in with sports fields, new buildings, and apartments. As the campus keeps growing, it's getting harder and harder to get from one place to another. So, what's the solution to this problem? On a college campus, it's gotta be the bicycle. But, let's be real, having a bike isn't enough - students need to actually ride them, and the campus needs to be set up to accommodate cyclists.

I was talking to a friend who just got back into biking after a few years off, and he was saying how he had no idea why he ever stopped. "Bikes are the way to go," he said. "For a few years, it wasn't cool to ride a bike, but it's the only way to get around." Not only is biking good for your body, but it's also the most efficient way to travel. You can eat a bowl of oatmeal and get 30 miles or more out of it - all while getting some exercise. I now live off campus, which is basically as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The best decision I made this year was buying a bike. Every day, I've got class in Thomas building, which is a 25-minute walk from my place. Riding a bike cuts that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest route to Thomas from my house, and it's not always the easiest road to travel on, bike or no bike. I've gotta say, walking has its pros, but personally, I'm too busy to walk. If I didn't have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option, and it would take up way too much of my time. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day, which is over two and a half hours every week. Add that to all the other time I'd spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and stuff, and that's just more time than I can spare.

In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). The following review focuses on insomnia, and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

	 The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspect of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons which are specifically responsible for sleep/ wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If it is inhibited from firing, this can cause reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results imply that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans. This shows that there is a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence with this receptor could alter the ability of one to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, this could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual. This would negatively impact aspects of life such as school, career, and every day events that involve monotonous tasks and focus.

This paper covers three areas of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is provided. Next, diagnosis is explained, with common characteristics, or “red flags”. Finally, the paper concludes with ways that a teacher in a mainstreamed classroom environment can assist a student with CAPD.

	Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) “refers to the efficiency and effectiveness by which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiologic activity that underlies that processing and gives rise to electrophysiologic auditory potentials” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), meaning it is a disorder wherein the central nervous system (i.e. the brain) cannot properly process things that are heard. People with CAPD can hear normally, and are therefore not considered “hearing impaired”; rather, the area of the brain that translates what we hear, separating words or differentiating conversation from background noise does not function as it typically should. 

	The earliest mention of the disorder that became CAPD is from the mid-1950s, called “auditory imperception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers were evaluating children with communicative disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura “introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference was held in 1977 that stimulated research on children with CAPD.
